==English==

===Etymology===
{{root|en|ine-pro|*bʰeh₂-|id=speak}}
From {{der|en|grc|φώνημα||sound}}, from {{m|grc|φωνέω||to sound}}, from {{m|grc|φωνή||sound}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|GA}} {{IPA|en|/ˈfoʊnim/}}
* {{a|RP}} {{IPA|en|/ˈfəʊniːm/}}
* {{audio|en|En-us-phoneme.ogg|Audio (US)}}
* {{rhymes|en|oʊnim|əʊniːm|s=2}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# An indivisible [[unit]] of [[sound]] in a given language. A phoneme is an abstraction of the physical speech sounds ([[phone]]s) and may encompass several different [[phone]]s.
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1990|author=Jarmo Lainio|editor= Durk Gorter|title=Fourth International Conference on Minority Languages: Western and Eastern European papers |chapter=Sweden Finnish — development or deterioration?|url=https://books.google.co.nz/books?id=3XG8aROt64QC&|page=31|publisher=Multilingual Matters|isbn=9781853591112|text=It is crucial for the '''phoneme''' structure of Finnish — traditionally /d/ has not been included in the Finnish [[phonotax]], but it fulfils the criteria of a '''phoneme''' (Karlsson, 1983: 66-7).}}

